  abstract = {The role of stratospheric water vapor (SWV) changes, in response to increasing \$\$\textbackslash hbox \{CO\}\_2\$\$, as a feedback component of quantitative significance for climate sensitivity has remained controversial. Here, we calculate the SWV climate feedback under abrupt \$\$\textbackslash hbox \{CO\}\_2\$\$quadrupling in the CMIP5 ensemble of models. All models robustly show a moistening of the stratosphere, causing a global mean net stratosphere adjusted radiative perturbation of \$\$0.89\textbackslash pm 0.27\textbackslash,\textbackslash hbox \{Wm\}\^\{-2\}\$\$at the reference tropopause. The stratospheric temperature adjustment is a crucial component of this radiative perturbation. The associated climate feedback is \$\$0.17\textbackslash pm 0.05\textbackslash,\textbackslash hbox \{Wm\}\^\{-2\}\textbackslash,\textbackslash hbox\{K\}\^\{-1\}\$\$, with a considerable inter-model range of 0.12\textendash 0.28 \$\$\textbackslash hbox \{Wm\}\^\{-2\}\textbackslash,\textbackslash hbox \{K\}\^\{-1\}\$\$. Taking into account the rise in tropopause height under \$\$4\textbackslash times \textbackslash hbox \{CO\}\_2\$\$slightly reduces the feedback to \$\$0.15\textbackslash pm 0.04\textbackslash,\textbackslash hbox \{Wm\}\^\{-2\}\textbackslash,\textbackslash hbox \{K\}\^\{-1\}\$\$, with a range of 0.10\textendash\$\$0.26\textbackslash,\textbackslash hbox \{Wm\}\^\{-2\} \textbackslash,\textbackslash hbox \{K\}\^\{-1\}\$\$. The SWV radiative perturbation peaks in the midlatitudes and not the tropics: this is due primarily to increases in SWV in the extratropical lowermost stratosphere, which cause the majority (over three quarters) of the global mean feedback. Based on these results, we suggest an increased focus on understanding drivers of water vapor trends in the extratropical lowermost stratosphere. We conclude that the SWV feedback is important, being on the same order of magnitude as the global mean surface albedo and cloud feedbacks in the multi-model mean.},
